ginally genre was not until the 16th century that fugal technique understood today began seen pieces both instrumental and vocal Fugal writing found works such fantasias ricercares and canzonas Fugue theoretical term first occurred 1330 when Jacobus Liege wrote about the fuga his Speculum musicae The fugue arose from the technique imitation where the same musical material was repeated starting different note Gioseffo Zarlino composer author and theorist the Renaissance was one the first distinguish between the two types imitative counterpoint fugues and canons which called imitations Originally this was aid improvisation but the 1550s was considered technique composition The Renaissance composer Giovanni Pierluigi Palestrina 15251594 wrote masses using modal counterpoint and imitation and fugal writing became the basis for writing motets well Palestrinas imitative motets differed from fugues that each phrase the text had different subject which was introduced and worked out separately whereas fugue continued working with the same subject subjects throughout the entire length the piece was the Baroque period that the writing fugues became central composition part demonstration compositional expertise Fugues were incorporated into variety musical forms Jan Pieterszoon Sweelinck Girolamo Frescobaldi Johann Jakob Froberger and Dieterich Buxtehude all wrote fugues and George Frideric Handel included them many his oratorios Keyboard suites from this time often conclude with fugal gigue Domenico Scarlatti has only few fugues among his corpus over 500 harpsichord sonatas The French overture featured quick fugal section after slow introduction The second movement sonata chiesa written Arcangelo Corelli and others was usually fugal The Baroque period also saw rise the importance music theory Some fugues during the Baroque period were pieces designed teach contrapuntal technique students The most influential text was Johann Joseph Fuxs Gradus Parnassum Steps Parnassus which appeared 1725 This work laid out the terms species counterpoint and offered series exercises learn fugue writing Fuxs work was largely based the practice Palestrinas modal fugues Mozart studied from this book and remained influential into the nineteenth century Haydn for example taught counterpoint from his own summary Fux and thought the basis for formal structure Bachs most famous fugues are those for the harpsichord The WellTempered Clavier which many composers and theorists look the greatest model fugue The WellTempered Clavier comprises two volumes written different times Bachs life each comprising prelude and fugue pairs one for each major and minor key Bach also known for his organ fugues which are usually preceded prelude toccata The Art Fugue BWV 1080 collection fugues and four canons single theme that gradually transformed the cycle progresses Bach also wrote smaller single fugues and put fugal sections movements into many his more general works Bachs influence extended forward through his son CPE Bach and through the theorist Friedrich Wilhelm Marpurg 17181795 whose Abhandlung von der Fuge Treatise the fugue 1753 was largely based Bachs work During the Classical era the fugue was longer central even fully natural mode musical composition Nevertheless both Haydn and Mozart had periods their careers which they some sense rediscovered fugal writing and used frequently their work Joseph Haydn was the leader fugal composition and technique the Classical era Haydns most famous fugues can found his Sun Quartets 1772 which three have fugal finales This was practice that Haydn repeated only once later his quartetwriting career with the finale his String Quartet 1787 Some the earliest examples Haydns use counterpoint however are three symphonies and that date from 176263 The earliest fugues both the symphonies and the Baryton trios exhibit the influence Joseph Fuxs treatise counterpoint Gradus Parnassum 1725 which Haydn studied carefully Haydns second fugal period oc